## Auth hardening

### No anonymous org access in production

Tokens without an explicit `organization_id` claim are rejected at the transport layer:
- HTTP: `auth_deps.get_current_user()` raises 401
- WebSocket (domain events): `ws_endpoint` closes with code 4001
- WebSocket (chat): `ws_chat_endpoint` closes with code 4001

This is gated on `is_deployed`. Dev/test tokens without `organization_id` fall back to `DEFAULT_ORG_ID = "default"` for local tooling compatibility.

### Auth provider is config-driven

`AUTH_PROVIDER` env var selects JWT claim shape:
- `supabase` (default) — role in `app_metadata.role`, user id in `sub`
- `internal` — role as top-level claim, user id in `user_id` or `sub`

Never add inline claim path-sniffing outside `shared/api/auth_provider.py`. All three auth entry points (HTTP, WS domain, WS chat) call `resolve_claims(payload)`.

### JWT secret requirements

- Production: `JWT_SECRET` must be set and must not be the dev default. Startup raises `RuntimeError` otherwise.
- Staging: same enforcement.
- Generate: `python -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_hex(32))"`

---

## Required env vars for production

```
ENV=production
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://...
JWT_SECRET=<64-char hex>
CORS_ORIGINS=https://your-app-domain.com
REDIS_URL=redis://redis:6379
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=<strong password>
AUTH_PROVIDER=supabase
```

Optional but recommended:
```
SENTRY_DSN=https://...
PG_POOL_MAX=10
WORKERS=2
```
